<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-02-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-02-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="147" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d147">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 PW/2–2246</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to President <persName type="to">Truman</persName></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left"><hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi></seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-02-22">February 22, 1946</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>This<note n="89" xml:id="d147fn1">See draft treaty, quoted in telegram
                                348, February 28, 3 p.m., to Moscow, <ref target="#pg_152">p.
                                    152</ref>.</note> is similar to the document I recently
                            submitted to you. I am proposing to submit this draft to UK, USSR and
                            China. I have not included France. Will talk to you about it.<note n="90" xml:id="d147fn2">President Truman wrote his reply in the
                                margin of this document as follows: “Jim:—I [am] very anxious that
                                our place in Pacific affairs should be a dominant one in the peace
                                as it has been in the war. H.S.T.”</note></p>
                        <closer><signed>J[<hi rend="smallcaps">ames</hi>] F. B[<hi rend="smallcaps">yrnes</hi>]</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>